Step 2: LeNet-5 Neural network architecture¶

Model Architecture¶

F: Filter | P: Padding | W: Width | S: Stride

Out = { (W F + 2P) / S } + 1

valid padding := zero padding

Input doesn't return a layer if you are using Sequential, you may also skip the Input and just specify the input_shape for the first Layer. model.add(Input(shape=(?, 32, 32, 3)))

Conv2D When using this layer (Conv2D) as the first layer in a model, provide the keyword argument input_shape (tuple of integers, does not include the sample axis), e.g. input_shape=(128, 128, 3) for 128x128 RGB pictures in data_format="channels_last".

Layer Default Property
Conv2D padding='valid', strides=(1, 1), use_bias=True, bias_initializer='zeros'
MaxPooling2D pool_size=(2, 2), strides=None, padding='valid'
Dense use_bias=True, bias_initializer='zeros'

General Advise: (from various blogs)

  • Everything being equal, smaller batches in the training set help a lot in order to increase the general performance of the network, as a negative side, the training process is much slower.

  • Dropout is useful in large networks with lots of data and lots of iterations, in my network I applied dropout on the final fully connected layers only, convolution layers did not get dropout applied.

  • Batch sizes are more important that one might think, apparently it is easier to hit a local minimum when batches are larger.

  • Usually, dropout is placed on the fully connected layers only because they are the one with the greater number of parameters and thus they're likely to excessively co-adapting themselves causing overfitting.

  • A rule of thumb is to set the keep probability (1 - drop probability) to 0.5 when dropout is applied to fully connected layers whilst setting it to a greater number (0.8, 0.9, usually) when applied to convolutional layers.

  • Dropout are not usually used for Conv Layers, following could be the reasons:

    • one of the reason is that the convolutional layers usually don't have all that many parameters, so they need less regularization to begin with.
    • Another is that, because the gradients are averaged over the spatial extent of the feature maps, dropout becomes ineffective: there end up being many correlated terms in the averaged gradient, each with different dropout patterns. So the net effect is that it only slows down training, but doesn't prevent co-adaptation. One way to mitigate this is to ensure that you apply the same dropout mask in every spatial position within a layer per example, but this may end up being too strong of a regularizer.

  • from the Srivastava/Hinton dropout paper:

    • The additional gain in performance obtained by adding dropout in the convolutional layers (3.02% to 2.55%) is worth noting. One may have presumed that since the convolutional layers dont have a lot of parameters, overfitting is not a problem and therefore dropout would not have much effect. However, dropout in the lower layers still helps because it provides noisy inputs for the higher fully connected layers which prevents them from overfitting.
    • They use 0.7 prob for conv drop out and 0.5 for fully connected.

  • Dropout affects all layers in the network, not just the one you put it in front (although this one is most strongly affected, for obvious reasons). So I guess it can indeed still make a difference. Another reason that comes to mind (for not adding dropout on the conv. layers) is that the approximation of disabling dropout at test time and compensating by reducing the weights by a factor of 1/(1 - dropout_rate) only really holds exactly for the last layer. For any other layers, it is an approximation, and this approximation gets worse as you get further away from the ouptut. In a typical architecture the convolutional layers come first, then followed by one or more dense layers, so they tend to be much farther from the output.

  • VGG-16 net uses dropout only for fc layers "The training was regularised by weight decay (the L2 penalty multiplier set to 5 * 10e-4) and dropout regularisation for the first two fully-connected layers (dropout ratio set to 0.5). The learning rate was initially set to 10e-2, and then decreased by a factor of 10 when the validation set accuracy stopped improving."

  • Between the linear transform and nonlinearity is the right place for the Batch normalization.

from tensorflow.keras import Sequential, regularizers
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D, MaxPooling2D, Dense, Flatten, Input, Dropout, Lambda, BatchNormalization, Activation
from tensorflow.keras.initializers import TruncatedNormal

 = 0.0
 = 5e-2
 = 5e-3
fc_drop_rate = 0.60

# input_shape = _IMG_SHAPE is applied if CONV2D is the 1st layer 
def add_batch_normed_conv_layer(model, name, depth = 64):
    model.add(Conv2D(depth, (3, 3),
            input_shape = _IMG_SHAPE,
            kernel_initializer = TruncatedNormal(mean=, stddev=),
            name = name))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('relu'))

def add_batch_normed_dense_layer(model, name, out):
    model.add(Dense(out,
                    kernel_initializer = TruncatedNormal(mean=, stddev=),
                    name = name))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(fc_drop_rate))


model = Sequential() # (?, 32, 32 ,1)

add_batch_normed_conv_layer(model, 'block1_conv1') # (?, 30, 30 ,64)
add_batch_normed_conv_layer(model, 'block1_conv2') # (?, 28, 28 ,64)
model.add(MaxPooling2D(strides = (2, 2))) # (?, 14, 14 ,64)

add_batch_normed_conv_layer(model, 'block2_conv1', 128) # (?, 12, 12 ,128)
add_batch_normed_conv_layer(model, 'block2_conv2', 128) # (?, 10, 10 ,128)
model.add(MaxPooling2D(strides = (2, 2))) # (?, 5, 5 ,128)

# In: (?, 5, 5, 128) | Out: (?, 3200) {1600 = 5 * 5 * 128}
model.add(Flatten(name='flatten'))

# 3200/3 ~ 1067
# 1067/3 ~ 357
# 357/3 ~ 118 ~~~ _NUM_CLASS ~ 43

add_batch_normed_dense_layer(model, "fc1", 1067) # (?, 1067)
add_batch_normed_dense_layer(model, "fc2", 357) # (?, 357)

model.add(Dense(_NUM_CLASS, activation='softmax',
                kernel_initializer = TruncatedNormal(mean=, stddev=),
                kernel_regularizer = regularizers.l2(),
                name='fc3')) # (?, _NUM_CLASS)

Train, Validate and Test the Model¶

A validation set can be used to assess how well the model is performing. A low accuracy on the training and validation sets imply underfitting. A high accuracy on the training set but low accuracy on the validation set implies overfitting.

model.fit() and model.evaluate() :when using tf.data as input make sure to include steps parameter

keras is not able to save model in default tesnsorflow checkpoint format, hence we use the h5 format

Callbacks

In [136]:
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping, TerminateOnNaN, TensorBoard, ReduceLROnPlateau, LearningRateScheduler

import pickle
import math

_EPOCHS = 150

_LOAD_MODEL = False

history = None

if not _LOAD_MODEL:
    
    lr_drop_patience = 3
    lr_drop_limit = 1e-6
    early_stop_patience = np.floor(np.log10(/lr_drop_limit))
    print("early_stop_patience : ", early_stop_patience)
    
    monitor_metric = "val_acc"
    
    callbacks = [
        EarlyStopping(monitor = monitor_metric, 
                      min_delta = 0.005,
                      patience = lr_drop_patience * early_stop_patience,
                      verbose = 1,
                      mode = "max"),
        ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor = monitor_metric, 
                          factor = 0.1, 
                          patience = lr_drop_patience,
                          verbose = 1,
                          mode = "max",
                          min_delta = 0.005,
                          min_lr = lr_drop_limit),
        TensorBoard(log_dir = tensorboard_log_dir,
                    batch_size = _BATCH_SIZE),
        TerminateOnNaN()
    ]
    
    historyObj = model.fit_generator(
        training_gen,
        steps_per_epoch = training_gen.__len__(),
        epochs = _EPOCHS,
        callbacks = callbacks,
        validation_data = validation_gen,
        validation_steps = validation_gen.__len__(),
        shuffle = True,
        verbose = 1
    )
    
    history = historyObj.history
    
    os.system("spd-say 'Model Trained'")
    
    print("\n\n")
    model.summary()
    print("\n\n")
    
    model.save_weights(model_chkpt_file)
    print("Saved model weights to disk")
    
    with open(train_hist_file, 'wb') as f:
        pickle.dump(history, f)
    print("Training history saved")
    
else:
    model.load_weights(model_chkpt_file)
    print("Model weights loaded from disk")

    with open(train_hist_file, 'rb') as f:
        history = pickle.load(f)
    print("Training history loaded from disk")

def get_ground_truth_and_predictions(gen):
    gen.reset()

    ground_truth = []
    predictions = np.empty([1, _NUM_CLASS])

    # if steps is set than batch_size must not be set

    for i in np.arange(gen.__len__()):
        X, y = gen.__getitem__(i)
        ground_truth.extend([np.where(r==1)[0][0] for r in y])
        batch_pred = model.predict_on_batch(X)
        predictions = np.vstack((predictions, batch_pred))

    predictions = predictions[1:, :]
    ground_truth = np.array(ground_truth)
    
    return ground_truth, predictions

from IPython.core.display import display, HTML

N, K = probabilities.shape
correct_pred_count = 0
correct_top_k_pred_count = 0

htmlMarkup = "<table>"
htmlMarkup += "<tr>"
htmlMarkup += "<th>Class#</th>"
htmlMarkup += "<th>Image</th>"
htmlMarkup += "<th>Label</th>"
htmlMarkup += "<th>Model Top {:d} Predictions</th>".format(top_k)

htmlMarkup += "</tr>"

for n in np.arange(N):
    style = ""
    if y_pred[n][0] == web_eg_db["y"][n]:
        correct_pred_count += 1
        correct_top_k_pred_count += 1
    elif web_eg_db["y"][n] in y_pred[n]: 
        style = "style='color: blue;'"
        correct_top_k_pred_count += 1
    else:
        style = "style='color: red;'"

    htmlMarkup += "<tr {}>".format(style)
    htmlMarkup += "<td>{}</td>".format(web_eg_db["y"][n])

    s = ""
    for k in np.arange(K):
        s += "<p>{:5.4f}, {} ({})</p>"\
                .format(probabilities[n][k],
                        class_name_dict[y_pred[n][k]],
                        y_pred[n][k])
    htmlMarkup += "<td>{}</td>".format(s)

    x = web_eg_db["X"][n].rfind("/")
    y = web_eg_db["X"][n].rfind(".")
    fileName = web_example_plots_dir + "/{:05d}/".format(web_eg_db["y"][n])\

    plot_bar_chart(predictions[n], "", "class num", "confidence", fileName)

    htmlMarkup += "<td><img src='{}' height='128' width='256'/></td>"\

htmlMarkup += "</table>"

Step 5: Visualize the Neural Network's State with Test Images¶

In [153]:
import math

"""
activation should be of shape (1, H, W, C)
plt_num: used to plot out multiple different weight feature map sets on the same block,
        just extend the plt number for each new feature map entry
"""

def visualize_conv_layer_out(activation, activation_min = -1, activation_max = -1, plt_num = 1):
    _, H, W, C = activation.shape
    num_cols = 4
    num_rows = 16
    featuremaps = activation.shape[3]
    plt.figure(figsize = (20, int(num_rows * H / 4.5))) # (width, height)
    
    for c in np.arange(C):
        # sets the number of feature maps to show on each row and column
        plt.subplot(num_rows, num_cols, c + 1)
        plt.axis('off')
        # displays the feature map number
        plt.title('Feature Map ' + str(c))
        
        if activation_min != -1 & activation_max != -1:
            plt.imshow(activation[0,:,:, c],
                       interpolation="nearest",
                       vmin = activation_min,
                       vmax = activation_max,
                       cmap = "gray")
        
        elif activation_max != -1:
            plt.imshow(activation[0,:,:, c],
                       interpolation="nearest",
                       vmax = activation_max,
                       cmap="gray")
        
        elif activation_min !=-1:
            plt.imshow(activation[0,:,:, c],
                       interpolation = "nearest",
                       vmin = activation_min,
                       cmap = "gray")
        
        else:
            plt.imshow(activation[0,:,:, c],
                       interpolation="nearest",
                       cmap = "gray")
    
    plt.show()
    plt.close()

# https://keras.io/getting-started/faq/#how-can-i-obtain-the-output-of-an-intermediate-layer

def get_intermediate_layer_output(X, layer_name = "block1_conv1"):
    layer = model.get_layer(name = layer_name)
    intermediate_layer_model = keras.Model(inputs = model.input,
                                           outputs = layer.output)
    return intermediate_layer_model.predict(X)
